00:04:07.275 --> 00:04:12.135
Going back a couple of thousands of years, there was no England or Scotland.

00:04:12.515 --> 00:04:15.555
There were a series of warring tribes in Britain.

00:04:16.575 --> 00:04:22.445
In the north of the country, in modern-day Scotland, there were the Picts and the Scots.

00:04:23.235 --> 00:04:28.125
And in the south, in modern-day England and Wales, there were tribes such

00:04:28.125 --> 00:04:34.105
as the Iceni, which you might remember from episode number 251 on Boudicca.

00:04:35.332 --> 00:04:39.822
When the Romans arrived, first in 55 BC and then

00:04:39.842 --> 00:04:44.392
properly in 43 AD, they landed in the south of Britain.

00:04:45.522 --> 00:04:50.882
This was purely for practical reasons; it was the closest land to Europe.

00:04:52.282 --> 00:04:57.522
The Romans occupied Britain for almost 400 years, mainly subduing the

00:04:57.522 --> 00:05:03.142
local tribes, and importantly, they only occupied the south of the country.

00:05:04.552 --> 00:05:11.232
To the north were murderous, violent tribes, barbarians, and the Romans did what

00:05:11.272 --> 00:05:17.142
all self-respecting powers do to keep unwanted invaders out: they built a wall.

00:05:18.562 --> 00:05:25.772
This wall came to be known as Hadrian’s Wall, and in fact you can still visit its ruins today.

00:05:26.602 --> 00:05:30.962
It is right at the northern part of England, close to the border with Scotland.

00:05:32.482 --> 00:05:37.322
The reason to mention this is that this artificial division of the country by the

00:05:37.322 --> 00:05:45.112
Romans served as the first division between what we know today as England and Scotland.

00:05:46.392 --> 00:05:50.762
Fast forward a few hundred years, and by the early 10th

00:05:50.762 --> 00:05:55.312
century both Scotland and England were their own kingdoms.

00:05:56.072 --> 00:05:59.012
No longer were they a collection of warring small

00:05:59.012 --> 00:06:03.732
tribes, but two countries ruled by their own kings.

00:06:05.262 --> 00:06:09.322
England was the more powerful kingdom in every sense.

00:06:09.672 --> 00:06:14.632
Its population was larger, 3 or 4 million to Scotland’s under a million.

00:06:15.152 --> 00:06:19.512
It had a more developed agricultural system, it was richer, it had

00:06:19.522 --> 00:06:23.942
better access to military technology, a bigger and better-trained army.

00:06:25.392 --> 00:06:31.822
And in the late 13th century the English king, Edward I, did what powerful

00:06:31.822 --> 00:06:37.022
kings do, he invaded his weaker neighbour, marching north into Scotland.

00:06:38.384 --> 00:06:43.712
There had been a complication when the king of Scotland, Alexander, had died without

00:06:43.722 --> 00:06:50.142
leaving a surviving direct male heir, and King Edward of England had seized his opportunity.

00:06:51.652 --> 00:06:55.442
What happened next was the Scottish Wars of Independence.

00:06:55.912 --> 00:07:00.522
It is a long and bloody story, and in fact, you may remember

00:07:00.592 --> 00:07:05.062
part of it from episode number 186, on William Wallace.

